<div id="c2">
<p>You write: &#8220;[Already-thin people] lose nothing if more people get thin.&#8221;</p>

<p>That strikes me as naive.  Social status is positional.  A large increase in the number of thin people would decrease the social advantage that already-thin people have, in the past, either gotten for free (through genetics), or worked for (through exercise etc.), or both.  Once these people lose the advantage of thinness, they&#8217;ll have to fall back on other qualities, e.g. an engaging personality or strength of character or whatever.</p>

<p>Although I&#8217;m a cynic, so I believe that much of the social value currently placed on thinness would simply be displaced onto other physical traits, e.g. muscle tone.</p>

<p class="posted">posted by <a rel="nofollow" href="http://abstractfactory.blogspot.com/">Cog</a>
